1. POS tagging samples only the first 5,000 tokens per episode (line 81). For Circe
   (50,979 tokens), this is under 10% of the text. Noun-verb ratio and adjective
   density may be unrepresentative, especially for episodes where style shifts
   mid-episode (Nausicaa's Gerty-to-Bloom pivot, Cyclops' barfly-to-interpolation
   alternation). Consider tagging the full text or at least a larger/stratified sample.

2. VADER sentiment samples only the first 500 sentences (line 91). For long episodes,
   this truncates the analysis. Circe has thousands of short stage-direction lines;
   sampling only the first 500 biases toward early material. Same concern for Eumaeus
   and Cyclops.

3. Flesch-Kincaid syllable counting samples only the first 3,000 alphabetic tokens
   (line 99). For episodes longer than ~7,000 alpha tokens, the readability score
   reflects only the opening portion. This is particularly problematic for Oxen of the
   Sun, whose style deliberately evolves through the episode.

4. The exercise specifies 25+ metrics; the script computes only 15. Missing metrics
   include: stemmer disagreement rate, non-English token proportion, named entities per
   1,000 tokens, entity type distribution, WordNet synset count, TF-IDF keywords,
   bigram perplexity, parse tree depth, graph density, alliteration density,
   classification features, Burrows' Delta, and cliche density. Many of these would
   require importing results from prior weeks' scripts.

5. The exercise asks for a radar chart (spider plot) comparing Telemachus, Sirens,
   Cyclops, and Eumaeus. The script does not produce a radar chart. Only three of the
   four required dashboard panels are generated.

6. The hapax_ratio is computed as hapax / total_types (line 78), i.e., the fraction of
   unique words that appear exactly once. This is a valid metric but differs from the
   more common definition of hapax ratio as hapax / total_tokens. The exercise says
   "hapax legomena ratio" without specifying the denominator. Worth clarifying or
   computing both.

7. The median sentence length calculation (line 117) uses integer division
   (len(sent_lengths)//2) without averaging the two middle values for even-length
   lists. For 16 episodes this is unlikely to matter much, but it is technically
   incorrect for even-count lists.

8. The TTR is computed on alpha_tokens (lowercase alphabetic only), but total_tokens
   includes punctuation and non-alphabetic tokens. The denominator of TTR
   (line 113: len(alpha_tokens)) is therefore smaller than total_tokens, which is
   fine — but the master table displays total_tokens alongside TTR without noting this
   discrepancy. A reader might expect TTR = total_types / total_tokens.

9. The error audit is hardcoded rather than computed. It catalogs known issues from
   prior weeks as string literals rather than re-running analyses to detect errors
   programmatically. The exercise asks for an "error distribution" visualization —
   whether errors concentrate in certain episodes or tools — which is not produced.

10. The correlation matrix hypothesis from the exercise (sentiment variance correlates
    with entity density) cannot be tested because named entity density is not among the
    computed metrics.
